	<article id="post-115" class="post-115 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-strategy-and-hints">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="../general-strategy-ends.html" rel="bookmark">General Strategy &#8211; Ends</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="../general-strategy-ends.html" title="3:06 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2017-07-03T15:06:29+00:00">July 3, 2017</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="../author/star-scythe_8.html" title="View all posts by Silent Zebra" rel="author">Silent Zebra</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
						<div class="comments-link">
				<a href="../general-strategy-ends.html#respond"><span class="leave-reply">Reply</span></a>			</div>
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p>This page introduces a simple concept of &#8220;ends&#8221;, intended to provide a framework to improve your general speed and ease of gameplay.</p>
<h1>Ends</h1>
<p>An &#8220;end&#8221; is what I call any tile that must be stepped on last, because there is only one path that leads to that tile and no paths back once you have gone to that tile. The simplest example can be found in Easy &#8211; 3:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-118" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063831-1-576x1024.png" alt="" width="576" height="1024" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063831-1-576x1024.png 576w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063831-1-169x300.png 169w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063831-1-768x1365.png 768w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063831-1.png 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /></p>
<p>The circled square is an &#8220;end&#8221;; it must be completed last, as there is only one tile leading to it (and you cannot go back on that one tile). If you decide to step on that tile before the end, you get stuck (as below).</p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-119" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101241-576x1024.png" alt="" width="576" height="1024" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101241-576x1024.png 576w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101241-169x300.png 169w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101241-768x1365.png 768w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101241.png 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /></p>
<p>How is this useful for gameplay? A rule: never create 2 (or more) ends. Any time you have 2 or more ends, you know that you cannot complete the level. With this knowledge, you can use the process of elimination to get rid of certain potential moves, making it easier to find the right move. For example, in the below situation, you have two ends, and are already stuck, so you can rule out this path:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-121" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063843-576x1024.png" alt="" width="576" height="1024" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063843-576x1024.png 576w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063843-169x300.png 169w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063843-768x1365.png 768w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-063843.png 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /></p>
<p>The one block sticking out, as above, is the easiest type of end to recognize. There are some other formations that are a bit harder to recognize as ends. One example below:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-122" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101848-576x1024.png" alt="" width="576" height="1024" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101848-576x1024.png 576w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101848-169x300.png 169w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101848-768x1365.png 768w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-101848.png 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /></p>
<p>In the above, the entire 6-block section is an end &#8211; there&#8217;s no way to clear this level from the position shown above.</p>
<p>One formation I want to point out in particular is the below, where you have one orphan yellow tile sticking out, but attached to a red tile; this pops up very frequently. This is not an end (by itself), because you can step to the yellow tile and step back. Recognizing this, you can make it a rule of thumb to leave these formations around, treating it as if the two-tile formation is a single yellow tile where the red tile is.</p>
<div id="attachment_123" style="width: 424px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-123" decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-123 size-full" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot.png" alt="" width="414" height="649" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot.png 414w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot-191x300.png 191w" sizes="(max-width: 414px) 100vw, 414px" /><p id="caption-attachment-123" class="wp-caption-text">By the way, guess which level this is from. It&#8217;s a puzzle game, so I have to give you some puzzles on this website too 🙂</p></div>
<p>The circled, as above, will not become an end when you take the path starting from the left, while the left tile will become an end if you move right first. The solution? Move left.</p>
<p>There are a few levels that can be solved entirely by identifying ends and using a process of elimination. The below is one example: it&#8217;s a lot easier once you figure out where the end is:</p>
<div id="attachment_126" style="width: 586px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-126" decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-126 size-large" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-103628-1-576x1024.png" alt="" width="576" height="1024" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-103628-1-576x1024.png 576w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-103628-1-169x300.png 169w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-103628-1-768x1365.png 768w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-103628-1.png 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /><p id="caption-attachment-126" class="wp-caption-text">I was nice enough to circle the end for you</p></div>
<p>When you get really good at identifying ends, you can make observations as follows: in the below screenshot, after only two moves, I already know the player is stuck. One end has to be created as the player moves from the left through the top circle (or you create the end on the left) and the other end is created at the bottom. By the way, since there&#8217;s no way to clear all the tiles at the bottom in one go, that has to be the end &#8211; a pretty big key to solving this level.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-128" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104228-576x1024.png" alt="" width="576" height="1024" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104228-576x1024.png 576w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104228-169x300.png 169w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104228-768x1365.png 768w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104228.png 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /></p>
<h1>Dead Ends</h1>
<p>This is sort of a subset of the above. In brief, there are certain formations that simply cannot be cleared. Avoid these at all times (and undo or reset if you ever see one). One of the most common ones is the orphaned red tile with only one yellow tile leading to it:</p>
<div id="attachment_127" style="width: 586px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-127" decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-127 size-large" src="../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104537-576x1024.png" alt="" width="576" height="1024" srcset="http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104537-576x1024.png 576w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104537-169x300.png 169w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104537-768x1365.png 768w, http://silentzebra.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screenshot_20170624-104537.png 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /><p id="caption-attachment-127" class="wp-caption-text">By the way, there&#8217;s another unclearable formation where the other red block is&#8230; And yes, it might be more challenging to replicate this screenshot than to properly clear this level.</p></div>
<p>Next: <a href="../general-strategy-rules-thumb.html">Rules of Thumb</a></p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
		<footer class="entry-meta">
